# Comment Discipline

Code should communicate intent through naming and structure, not through comments that restate what the code already says. Redundant comments are noise — they rot faster than the code they describe and teach developers to stop reading them.

## Inline comments

Do not add comments that describe what the next line does. If the code needs a comment to be understood, rename the variable or extract a method.

### Bad

```csharp
// Get the order from the database
var order = await repository.GetByIdAsync(id, ct);

// Check if the order is null
if (order is null)
    return Result.NotFound();

// Map to response
return Result.Success(MapToResponse(order));
```

### Good

```csharp
var order = await repository.GetByIdAsync(id, ct);
if (order is null)
    return Result.NotFound();

return Result.Success(MapToResponse(order));
```

The code reads fine without the comments. Every comment was restating the obvious.

## When inline comments ARE useful

Comments that explain *why* — not *what* — earn their place. Business rules, non-obvious constraints, workarounds for external system quirks.

```csharp
// Courier API returns 200 with empty body when the shipment is still queued.
// We treat this as "pending" rather than an error.
if (response.IsSuccessStatusCode && string.IsNullOrEmpty(body))
    return DeliveryStatus.Pending;
```

## XML documentation (///)

Keep `///` on public API surfaces where the doc adds information beyond what the method signature already communicates. Do not add `///` to every public method just because a linter suggests it.

### Good — adds context

```csharp
/// <summary>
/// Calculates the fee based on distance tiers. Returns zero for distances
/// under the minimum threshold defined in tenant configuration.
/// </summary>
public decimal CalculateDeliveryFee(decimal distanceKm)
```

### Bad — restates the signature

```csharp
/// <summary>
/// Gets the order by id.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="id">The id.</param>
/// <returns>The order.</returns>
public Task<Order?> GetByIdAsync(long id, CancellationToken ct)
```
